{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:39:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"890"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/890"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.8,0.05,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/890"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93587"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"299"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman who is currently 36 weeks pregnant presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of ruptured membranes. She describes a large amount of pink-tinged fluid leaking while she was hanging washing on the line. She reports worsening abdominal pain coming every 3-4 minutes. This is her second pregnancy, with one previous vaginal birth. Until now the pregnancy has been uncomplicated. The routine test for group B streptococcus at 35 weeks gestation was positive. Fetal movements are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her local hospital is five minutes from her home, and she states her preference for a natural birth unless there are strong indications for a caesarean.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, oxygen saturation 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a fundal height of 34 cm, singleton fetus with longitudinal lie, cephalic presentation and 1/5 palpable. There is no uterine tenderness. A speculum examination shows liquor pooling in the posterior fornix. The cervix appears 4 cm dilated with fetal scalp visible. The fetal heart rate is 150/min and the cardiotocograph is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","IV benzylpenicillin","Tocolysis with nifedipine","IM betamethasone","Oral erythromycin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with preterm prelabour rupture of membranes (PPROM) and is now in established labour at 36 weeks gestation. She has a positive group B streptococcus (GBS) test at 35 weeks, which requires intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis to reduce the risk of early-onset neonatal GBS infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV benzylpenicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. It is the first-line antibiotic for intrapartum GBS prophylaxis. The initial dose is 3g IV, followed by 1.5g IV every 4 hours until delivery. Intravenous administration ensures rapid achievement of therapeutic levels in both maternal and fetal circulation, which is crucial during active labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for intrapartum GBS prophylaxis. Oral antibiotics do not achieve adequate serum levels quickly enough during labour to provide effective prophylaxis against vertical transmission of GBS to the neonate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETocolysis with nifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this case as the patient is already in established labour at 36 weeks gestation with a cervix that is 4 cm dilated. Attempting to stop labour at this stage is not recommended practice and would delay appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIM betamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the fetus is greater than 34 weeks and 6 days gestation. Antenatal corticosteroids for fetal lung maturation are most beneficial before 35 weeks gestation. At 36 weeks, the number needed to treat to prevent respiratory morbidity is much higher and not routinely recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral erythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate as part of the management of PPROM if the patient was not in labour, typically given for 10 days or until delivery. However, once labour is established in a GBS-positive woman, IV benzylpenicillin is the preferred antibiotic for intrapartum prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient should include admission, confirmation of fetal wellbeing, appropriate monitoring during labour, and administration of IV benzylpenicillin for GBS prophylaxis. Given that she is already 36 weeks gestation with established labour and normal cardiotocography, expectant management with appropriate antibiotic prophylaxis is the most appropriate approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intravenous benzylpenicillin is the first-line antibiotic for intrapartum group B streptococcus prophylaxis in women with preterm pre-labour rupture of membranes.","Women with group B streptococcus bacteriuria during pregnancy should receive intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis regardless of subsequent swab results.","Preterm pre-labour rupture of membranes with established labour requires immediate intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis rather than oral antibiotics or tocolysis."],"references":["Thomson, AJ, on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists.\u00a0Care of Women Presenting with Suspected Preterm Prelabour Rupture of Membranes from 24+0\u00a0Weeks of Gestation.BJOG\u00a02019;\u00a0126:e152\u2013166.","Kenyon, SL, Taylor, DJ, Tarnow-Mordi, W (2001): Broad spectrum antibiotics for preterm, prelabour rupture of fetal membranes: the ORACLE I randomised trial.\u00a0THE LANCET, Vol 357, pp979-988.","Caughey, A.B, Robinson, J.N, Norwitz, E.R (2008): Contemporary Diagnosis and Management of Preterm Premature Rupture of Membranes.\u00a0Rev Obstet Gynecol.\u00a01(1):11-22.","Parry, S, Strauss, JF (1998): Premature Rupture of the Fetal Membranes.\u00a0New England Journal of Medicine\u00a0Vol 338 (10) pp 663-675.","Boland, R.A., Davis, P.G., Dawson, J.A., Stewart, M.J., Smith, J. and Doyle, L.W. (2018), Very preterm birth before arrival at hospital. Aust N Z J Obstet Gynaecol, 58: 197-203. doi:10.1111/ajo.12690"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93587"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"890"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93587"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-15T09:14:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T21:38:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"890"}},"content":{"dat